{{Orphan|date=September 2017}}
'''Topaz Slough Wildlife Management Area''' ('''Topaz Slough WMA''') or '''Topaz Marsh''' is a marsh system that is part of the old [[Sevier River]] bed.
The water source stems from springs and irrigation runoff.<ref>[https://wildlife.utah.gov/waterfowl/forecasts_2015/clear_lake.php Clear Lake, Topaz Slough, Redmond and Bicknell Bottoms Waterfowl Management Areas]</ref>
== Fauna == Topaz Slough WMA is a historical use area for waterfowl and marsh dwelling species. Many different species of birds such as [[duck]]s, [[coot]]s, [[geese]], [[kestrel]]s, [[great blue heron]]s, and various shoreline birds can be found during the year.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7xszAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=%22topaz+marsh%22+utah&source=bl&ots=L8dKrLh6vG&sig=leAMQu4hFDXnNEWBiEAMtTkQ4NI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIxt_2_oXWAhUJUlAKHQ5HAQM4ChDoAQgsMAA#v=onepage&q=%22topaz%20marsh%22%20utah&f=false|title=Central Utah Project, Bonneville Unit: Environmental Impact Statement|date=1973|language=en}}</ref>
Occasionally, big animals like [[antelope]] use water on the west side of the slough. Furbearers include coyote, badger, red fox, and muskrat. Small game species that inhabit the WMA include cottontail rabbits, ring-necked pheasants, and mourning doves.<ref>[http://www.frankstehno.com/sagemesa/destinations/utah/north/topazwma/index.htm Topaz Slough Wildlife Management Area]</ref>
